oks at the language in which the Bible is written, arguing that it is identical to that of myth and metaphor. Frye suggests, therefore, that given this characteristic, the Bible should be read imaginatively rather than historically or doctrinally. However, he is also careful to point out the ways in which the Bible is more than a conventional work of fiction. The second half is an astonishing tour de force in which Frye demonstrates how both the Bible and literature revolve around four primary concerns of human life.This edition goes beyond the original in its documentation of Frye's dazzlingly encyclopedic range of reference. Profound and searching, Words with Power is perhaps the most daring book of Frye's career and one of the most exciting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aBible and literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aDolzani, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268964040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442689640423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442689640.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles